title: Silent Spring Text Analysis
description: A text and sentiment analysis of Rachel Carson's Silent Spring.
contents:
Text Analysis-Silent Spring by Rachel Carson
Introduction
Silent Spring by Rachel Carson is one the seminal texts of 20th century. It brought greater environmental awareness regarding chemicals and their impacts. A text and sentiment analysis of Silent Spring can yield some insight on this important book.
Silent Spring is available for download as free PDF online. Below is page 47 of Silent Spring after reading in the downloaded .pdf using pdf_text(here()).


hide

silent_spring_text <- pdf_text(here("_posts", "2021-03-15-silent-spring", "data", "silent_spring.pdf"))


silent_spring_p47 <- silent_spring_text[47]
silent_spring_p47


[1] "and having complete control over their material. Sometimes compressor pumps and material\r\ncan be mounted on truck chassis, but there is no blanket spraying. Treatment is directed only to\r\ntrees and any exceptionally tall shrubs that must be eliminated. The integrity of the\r\nenvironment is thereby preserved, the enormous value of the wildlife habitat remains intact,\r\nand the beauty of shrub and fern and wildflower has not been sacrificed. Here and there the\r\nmethod of vegetation management by selective spraying has been adopted. For the most part,\r\nentrenched custom dies hard and blanket spraying continues to thrive, to exact its heavy\r\nannual costs from the taxpayer, and to inflict its damage on the ecological web of life. It thrives,\r\nsurely, only because the facts are not known. When taxpayers understand that the bill for\r\nspraying the town roads should come due only once a generation instead of once a year, they\r\nwill surely rise up and demand a change of method.\r\nAmong the many advantages of selective spraying is the fact that it minimizes the amount of\r\nchemical applied to the landscape. There is no broadcasting of material but, rather,\r\nconcentrated application to the base of the trees. The potential harm to wildlife is therefore\r\nkept to a minimum. The most widely used herbicides are 2,4-D, 2,4,5-T, and related\r\ncompounds. Whether or not these are actually toxic is a matter of controversy. People spraying\r\ntheir lawns with 2,4-D and becoming wet with spray have occasionally developed severe\r\nneuritis and even paralysis. Although such incidents are apparently uncommon, medical\r\nauthorities advise caution in use of such compounds. Other hazards, more obscure, may also\r\nattend the rise of 2,4-D. It has been shown experimentally to disturb the basic physiological\r\nprocess of respiration in the cell, and to imitate X-rays in damaging the chromosomes. Some\r\nvery recent work indicates that reproduction of birds may be adversely affected by these and\r\ncertain other herbicides at levels far below those that cause death. Apart from any directly toxic\r\neffects, curious indirect results follow the use of certain herbicides. It has been found that\r\nanimals, both wild herbivores and livestock, are sometimes strangely attracted to a plant that\r\nhas been sprayed, even though it is not one of their natural foods. If a highly poisonous\r\nherbicide such as arsenic has been used, this intense desire to reach the wilting vegetation\r\ninevitably has disastrous results. Fatal results may follow, also, from less toxic herbicides if the\r\nplant itself happens to be poisonous or perhaps to possess thorns or burs. Poisonous range\r\nweeds, for example, have suddenly become attractive to livestock after spraying, and the\r\nanimals have died from indulging this unnatural appetite. The literature of veterinary medicine\r\nabounds in similar examples: swine eating sprayed cockleburs with consequent severe illness,\r\nlambs eating sprayed thistles, bees poisoned by pasturing on mustard sprayed after it came\r\ninto bloom. Wild cherry, the leaves of which are highly poisonous, has exerted a fatal attraction\r\nfor cattle once its foliage has been sprayed with 2,4-D. Apparently the wilting that follows\r\nspraying (or cutting) makes the plant attractive. Ragwort has provided other examples.\r\nLivestock ordinarily avoid this plant unless forced to turn to it in late winter and early spring by\r\nlack of other forage. However, the animals eagerly feed on it after its foliage has been sprayed\r\nwith 2,4-D. The explanation of this peculiar behavior sometimes appears to lie in the changes\r\nwhich the chemical brings about in the metabolism of the plant itself. There is temporarily a\r\nmarked increase in sugar content, making the plant more attractive to many animals.\r\nAnother curious effect of 2,4-D has important effects for livestock, wildlife, and apparently for\r\nmen as well. Experiments carried out about a decade ago showed that after treatment with this\r\nchemical there is a sharp increase in the nitrate content of corn and of sugar beets. The same\r\n"

Before pursing further textual analysis, the text of Silent Spring needs to be converted into a “data.frame()” and the fact that lines are separated by  needs to be addressed. Using “str_split()” the text can be broken into individual lines, and further wrangled for analysis using “unnest()” and “mutate(text_full = str_trim())”.


hide

silent_spring_tidy <- data.frame(silent_spring_text) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_split(silent_spring_text, pattern = '\\r')) %>% 
  unnest(text_full) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_trim(text_full)) 



So this textual anlysis is concentrating on the body of Silent Spring, the introduction and post-body text can be removed using “slice()”.


hide

silent_spring_df <- silent_spring_tidy %>% 
  slice(201:6201) 



The text of Silent Spring is converted into tokens with “unnest_tokens()”. The number of times words appear is the determined using “count()” and stop words (but, and, the, etc.) are removed using “anti_join(stop_words)”.


hide

silent_spring_tokens <- silent_spring_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text_full) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-silent_spring_text)

silent_spring_wordcount <- silent_spring_tokens %>% 
  count(word)

silent_spring_nonstop_words <- silent_spring_tokens %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words)


nonstop_counts <- silent_spring_nonstop_words %>% 
  count(word)



To get the top 100 words “arrange() %>% slice(1:100)”. The top two words are “chemicals” and “chemical”, with “ddt” and “spraying” also making the top 5.


hide

top100 <- nonstop_counts %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  slice(1:100)





hide

ddt_background <- readJPEG(here("_posts", "2021-03-15-silent-spring", "data", "ddt_spraying.jpg"))



Visualizations
A word cloud of the top 100 words is produced using “ggplot() + geom_text_wordcloud”.


hide

silent_spring_cloud <- ggplot(data = top100, aes(label = word)) +
  annotation_custom(rasterGrob(ddt_background, 
                               width = unit(1,"npc"), 
                               height = unit(1,"npc")), 
                    -Inf, Inf, -Inf, Inf) +
  geom_text_wordcloud(aes(color = n, size = n), shape = "pentagon") +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 6) +
  scale_color_gradientn(colors = c("red", "yellow")) +
  theme_minimal()

silent_spring_cloud




Figure 1: Silent Spring Wordcloud. Data: Silent Spring, Rachel Carson (1962)


hide

top20 <- top100 %>% 
  slice(1:20) %>% 
  group_by(-n) 

ddt_for_me <- readJPEG(here("_posts", "2021-03-15-silent-spring", "data", "ddt1.jpg"))



A column graph of the Top 20 words in Silent Spring.


hide

silent_spring_column <- ggplot(data = top20, aes(x = reorder(word, n), y = n)) +
  annotation_custom(rasterGrob(ddt_for_me, 
                               width = unit(1,"npc"), 
                               height = unit(1,"npc")), 
                    -Inf, Inf, -Inf, Inf) +
  geom_col(aes(alpha = 0), show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = cols,
    aesthetics = c("colour", "fill")
  ) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Word in Silent Spring by Rachel Carson",
       y = "Count",
       x = "Word") +
  theme_classic()
  
  

silent_spring_column




Figure 2: Silent Spring Top 20 Words Column Plot. Data: Silent Spring, Rachel Carson (1962)
NRC sentiment analysis with “inner_join(get_sentiments())”.


hide

silent_spring_nrc <- silent_spring_nonstop_words %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc"))

silent_spring_nrc_counts <- silent_spring_nrc %>% 
  count(sentiment)

ddt_plane <- readJPEG(here("_posts", "2021-03-15-silent-spring", "data", "ddt_plane.jpg"))

ggplot(data = silent_spring_nrc_counts, aes(x = sentiment, y = n, color = "red")) +
  annotation_custom(rasterGrob(ddt_plane, 
                               width = unit(1,"npc"), 
                               height = unit(1,"npc")), 
                    -Inf, Inf, -Inf, Inf) +
  geom_col(aes(alpha = 0.5), show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Silent Spring NRC Sentiment Analysis",
       x = "Sentiment",
       y = "Word Count")




Figure 3: Silent Spring NRC Sentiment Analysis. Data: Silent Spring, Rachel Carson (1962)
Citation
Data: Silent Spring, Rachel Carson (1962)

title: Visualization of Mono Lake Level
description: Wrangling and visualization of Mono Lake surface level.
contents:
Annual Water Level of Mono Lake, 1850-2017


Show code

knitr::include_graphics("./data/mono_lake.jpg")




Photo by Aaron Kreisberg
Intoduction
The levels of Mono Lake will be wrangled and explored using the tidyverse package. Data will be visualized using ggplot. Find more information about Mono Lake at https://www.monolake.org/learn/stateofthelake/


Show code

ggplot(data = mono_lake_annual_levels, aes(x = year, 
                                           y = lake_level_feet_above_sea_level)) +
  geom_line(color = "deepskyblue", size = 1.5) + #Visualize lake level with a line geom_line())
  geom_hline(yintercept = 6377, linetype="dashed", color = "red", size = 1.5) +  #Line for land bridges
  annotate(geom = "text", #Annotate land bridge line
           x = 1875,
           y = 6380,
           label = "Land Bridges Appear") +
  geom_point(data = mono_dates, 
             shape = "*", 
             size = 15) +
    geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = -Inf, ymax = lake_level_feet_above_sea_level), fill = "blue", alpha = 0.25) + #Fill in the area under the line geom_ribbon()
  geom_hline(yintercept = 6392, linetype="dashed", size = 1.5) + #Line for stable level
  annotate(geom = "text", #Annotate stable line
           x = 1875,
           y = 6395,
           label = "Managment Level Objective") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 6360, color = "orange", size = 1.5) + #Line for salinity impacts
  annotate(geom = "text", #Annotate initial salinity line
           x = 1875,
           y = 6363,
           label = "Initial Salinity Impacts") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 6350, color = "yellow", size = 1.5) + #Line for acute salinity impacts
   annotate(geom = "text", #Annotate acute salinity line
           x = 1875,
           y = 6353,
           label = "Acute Salinity Impacts") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1850, 1875, 1900, 1925, 1950, 1975, 2000, 2017)) + #Relabel x-axis ticks
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(6350, 6375, 6400, 6425)) + #Relabel y-axis ticks
  expand_limits(y = c(6350, 6430)) + #Expand y-axis range
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Lake Level (feet above sea level)") +
  geom_label(aes(label="Water Diversions Initiatied", #Use geom_label() to add labels to key points
    x=1952,
    y=6421.0)) +
   geom_label(aes(label="MLC/NAS sue LADWP", 
    x=1979,
    y=6369)) +
  geom_label(aes(label="Public Trust Decision", 
    x=1978,
    y=6383)) +
  geom_label(aes(label="1631 Decision", 
    x=2008,
    y=6373)) +
  theme_minimal() #Adjust theme




Figure 1. Annual Water Level of Mono Lake, 1850-2017. Key dates (1941-Water Diversions Initiated, 1979-Mono Lake Committee and National Audubon Society sue Los Angeles Department of Water and Power, 1983-Public Trust Decision, 1994-“1631” Decision, 2013-Restoration Agreement) and key management water levels (black line at “6392 ft Stable Level” called for by restoration agreement, red line at 6377 ft level where land bridges form impacting nesting birds with increased predation, orange (6360 ft) and yellow (6350 ft) lines representing levels where lake salinity impacts ecology initially and acutely respectively) are noted. Data: Mono Basin Clearinghouse

title: Urchins Analysis
description: Analysis of Sea Urchins at Santa Barbara County Long-Term Ecological Research Site.
contents:
Data regarding sea urchins collected through the Santa Barbara Coastal Long-Term Ecological Research site will be examined to display data wrangling and statistical analysis.
Part 1
First the urchins.csv file will be read in using read.csv(here(“data”, “urchins.csv”)) from the data folder in the R.project, and names will be cleaned using clean_names()


hide

urchins <- read.csv(here("_posts", "2021-03-12-urchins","data", "urchin.csv")) %>% 
  clean_names()



Section 1 - Size Comparison of purple and red urchins
Exploratory data visualization of purple and red urchins
First the distribution of sizes of purple and red urchins will be examined visually. This will be done by using gg_plot, with both a faceted histogram (ggplot() + geom_histogram + facet_wrap(~common_name)) and a boxplot (ggplot() + geom_boxplot())


hide

ggplot(data = urchins, aes(x = size, fill = common_name)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "black") +
  facet_wrap(~common_name) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("purple", "red")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(x = "Urchin Size (diameter to the nearest 0.5 cm)", y = "# of Urchins")






hide

ggplot(data = urchins, aes(x = common_name, y = size, fill = common_name)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("purple", "red")) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(x = "Urchins", y ="Urchin Size (nearest 0.5 cm)")




Descriptive statistics table of purple and red urchins data
Next the data will be explored in a summary statistics table by using goup_by(common_name) followed by summarise(mean(), median (), sd(), and n()). The kbl() from the kableExtra package will improve the aesthetics of the summary statistics table


hide

urchin_stats <- urchins %>%
  group_by(common_name) %>% 
  summarise(mean_size = mean(size),
            median_size = median(size),
            sd_size = sd(size), 
            n = n()) 
kbl(urchin_stats) %>% 
  kable_classic(full_width = TRUE)



common_name


mean_size


median_size


sd_size


n


Purple Urchin


4.469797


4.5


1.175264


31805


Red Urchin


6.776489


7.0


1.891343


27408


hide

actual_difference = (6.776489-4.469797)
actual_difference


[1] 2.306692

hide

percent_difference = ((6.776489-4.469797)/((6.776489+4.469797)/2))*100
percent_difference


[1] 41.0214

Based on the above exploratory graphs and table, both populations appear to relatively normally distributed with purple maybe showing a slight positive skew and red urchins showing more upper range outliers. Based on summary statistics, red urchins show a greater mean and median size, and a larger standard deviation, although there is a greater number of purple urchins (n = 31805) versus red urchins (n = 27408). The actual difference between mean urchin diameter is ~2.31, while the percent difference (calculated in the code section above) is ~41%; the mean red urchin is 41% larger in diameter than the mean purple urchin which can be a more useful comparison then just a actual difference depending on the comparison.
Section 2 - Exploration of purple urchin counts by site and year
In a piped sequence of code a subset of the urchins data will be created. A new column is created to convert the date to class “Date” and creating a colunm with just the year.


hide

purple_urchins <- urchins %>%
    mutate(date_new = mdy(date)) %>% # Convert the date to class "Date" ~mdy(date)
  filter(common_name == "Purple Urchin") %>% # Filter for only the purple urchins ~filter()
  mutate(year = year(date_new)) %>% # Create a column with just the date ~mutate(year())
  mutate(site_full = case_when( # Create a new column with full names for sites case_when() 
    site == "NAPL" ~ "Naples Reef", 
    site == "AQUE" ~ "Arroyo Quemado Reef", 
    site == "CARP" ~ "Carpinteria Reef",
    site == "MOHK" ~ "Mohawk Reef",
    site == "IVEE" ~ "Isla Vista Reef"))

# Create a summary table of # of purple urchins by site and year, using the group_by() and count()
purple_urchin_site_year <- purple_urchins %>% 
  group_by(year, site_full) %>% 
  count(site_full)
  
purple_urchin_site_year  


# A tibble: 61 x 3
# Groups:   year, site_full [61]
    year site_full               n
   <dbl> <chr>               <int>
 1  2008 Arroyo Quemado Reef    67
 2  2008 Carpinteria Reef      265
 3  2008 Mohawk Reef           294
 4  2008 Naples Reef           246
 5  2009 Arroyo Quemado Reef   926
 6  2009 Carpinteria Reef     1315
 7  2009 Mohawk Reef          1344
 8  2009 Naples Reef          1064
 9  2010 Arroyo Quemado Reef   921
10  2010 Carpinteria Reef      930
# ... with 51 more rows



hide

# Create an exploratory graph of counts of purple urchins at each site by year. This was done with ggplot() + geom_col() + facet_wrap()

ggplot(data = purple_urchin_site_year, aes(x = year, y = n, fill = site_full)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~site_full)




Part Two
Naples Reef Purple Urchins
The urchins data will be wrangled to compare the mean size of purple urchins in ANNUAL (annual giant kelp removal) and CONTROL (no giant kelp removal) sections of Naples Reef in January 2010. Summary statistics are determined and a two sample t-test is performed
Data Wrangling
First some basic data wrangling will be performed so the urchins data matches the above mentioned parameters. The mutate() will be used to: convert the date ~mdy() with the lubridate package and create columns using ~year() and ~month(). Then date will be filtered for Jan 2010 data ~filter(month == 01, year ==2010) of purple urchins at the Naples Reef site ~filter(common_name == “Purple Urchin”, site == “NAPL”). Lastly a new column will be created for site when it is NAPL that list the full name “Naples Reef” ~mutate(site_full = case_when(site == “NAPL” ~ “Naples Reef”))


hide

jan_2010_naples_urchins <- urchins %>%
  mutate(date_new = mdy(date)) %>% 
  mutate(year = year(date_new)) %>% 
  mutate(month = month(date_new)) %>% 
  filter(month == 01, year == 2010) %>% 
  filter(common_name == "Purple Urchin", site == "NAPL") %>%
  mutate(site_full = case_when(
  site == "NAPL" ~ "Naples Reef"))



Data Visualization
A histogram is created using ~ggplot(data = jan_2010_naples_urchins, aes(x = size, fill = treatment)) + geom_histogram(bins = 15) + facet_wrap(~treatment)


hide

ggplot(data = jan_2010_naples_urchins, aes(x = size, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 15) +
  facet_wrap(~treatment)




A QQ-plot for the size distribution is created by using ~ggplot(data = jan_2010_naples_urchins, aes(sample = size, color = treatment)) + geom_qq() + facet_wrap(~treatment)


hide

ggplot(data = jan_2010_naples_urchins, aes(sample = size, color = treatment)) +
  geom_qq() +
  facet_wrap(~treatment)




Each group shows a bimodal distribution in terms of numbers of urchins in relation to urchin diameter. There is also an appearance of a slight positive skew for each distribution with drawn out right tails representing larger urchin diameter, particularly in the ANNUAL treatment with two urchins six cm in diameter.
Summary Statistics Table
A summary statistics table that displays for purple urchins the mean size, the median size, the standard deviation, and the number in terms of the ANNUAL (annual giant kelp removal) and CONTROL (no giant kelp removal) treatments in January 2010 at Naples Reef. This is done by ~jan_2010_naples_urchins %>% group_by(treatment) %>% summarise(mean_size = mean(size), median_size = median(size), sd_size = sd(size), n = n()) %>% kbl() %>% kable_classic(full_width = TRUE)
Also the mean difference and percent difference between the annual and control treatments will be calculated


hide

jan_2010_naples_urchins %>%
  group_by(treatment) %>% 
  summarise(mean_size = mean(size),
            median_size = median(size),
            sd_size = sd(size), 
            n = n(),
            .groups = 'drop') %>% 
  kbl() %>% 
  kable_classic(full_width = TRUE)



treatment


mean_size


median_size


sd_size


n


ANNUAL


3.916667


4.0


0.9662380


60


CONTROL


3.725807


3.5


0.8668646


62


hide

mean_difference = (3.916667-3.725807)
mean_difference


[1] 0.19086

hide

percent_difference = ((3.916667-3.725807)/((3.916667+3.725807)/2))*100
percent_difference


[1] 4.994718

Two Sample t-test
A two sample t-test of is performed to compare the means of the annual and control treaments. This is done ~filter(treatment == “ANNUAL”) %>% pull(size), filter(treatment == “CONTROL”) %>% pull(size), and t.test(x = annual_sample, y = control_sample)


hide

annual_sample <- jan_2010_naples_urchins %>% 
  filter(treatment == "ANNUAL") %>% 
  pull(size)

control_sample <- jan_2010_naples_urchins %>% 
  filter(treatment == "CONTROL") %>% 
  pull(size)

t.test(x = annual_sample, y = control_sample)



    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  annual_sample and control_sample
t = 1.1472, df = 117.66, p-value = 0.2536
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -0.1386165  0.5203369
sample estimates:
mean of x mean of y 
 3.916667  3.725806 

The mean diameter of annual treatment purple urchins (3.92) is 0.19 greater then the control treatment (3.73), and the mean annual purple urchin has a diameter about 5% larger then the mean control purple urchin’s diameter. Based on these values, and considering standard deviations (or square roots of the diameter variance) close to 1 cm, there does not seem to be a significant amount of difference between these two populations based on whether they where in an annual or control treatment. Depending on the value placed on statistical significance, the high p-value could support this point of view. This p-value (0.2536) means that there is a ~25% probability that two samples with means this different would be randomly drawn from urchin populations with the same mean, and the null hypothesis of these means being drawn from the same population would not be rejected if using a p-value=0.05 for statistical significance.
Citation
-Reed, D. 2020. SBC LTER: Reef: Long-term experiment: Kelp removal: Urchin size frequency distribution ver 20. Environmental Data Initiative. https://doi.org/10.6073/pasta/5a1e9ef03aa47bd2225c0bb98a02a63b.

title: Spatial Analysis
description: Spatial analysis of 2008 California oil spills and California cetacean species richness.
